WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:04.720
At Posit, we want to be the open source data science company.

00:00:04.720 --> 00:00:09.040
As a public benefit corporation, we do more than just sell software our users love.

00:00:09.040 --> 00:00:13.040
We aim to make software for data science and scientific and technical computing

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:16.000
available to everyone, regardless of their ability to pay.

00:00:16.559 --> 00:00:20.559
We believe that the best way to create data science and scientific discoveries

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:23.920
that are reliable and reproducible is through code.

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:28.320
So our focus is helping people who write code generate value in their organizations more

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:28.879
efficiently.

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:34.480
We take a holistic approach to this goal, innovating on free and open source software,

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:38.880
making it easier for individual data professionals to create value in R

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:40.560
and the Python programming languages.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:45.840
At the same time, we want our professional tools to be the standard for writing and sharing

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:47.439
open source data science.

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:51.759
We are relentlessly focused on creating the best ways for people to create,

00:00:51.759 --> 00:00:56.000
deploy, and use core open source data science capabilities at scale.

00:00:56.720 --> 00:01:00.240
As you'll see in the rest of this demo, that means creating the best environment

00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:03.680
for people to develop and share content in R and Python.

00:01:04.480 --> 00:01:07.279
We believe that means not trying to reinvent the wheel,

00:01:07.279 --> 00:01:12.080
but instead to build first class business and technical integrations to BI tools,

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:15.919
MLOps frameworks, generative AI, data stores, and more.

00:01:16.639 --> 00:01:19.760
To get started, let's first introduce you to Posit Team.

00:01:21.279 --> 00:01:25.040
Posit Team is a bundled offering of our three professional tools,

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:29.040
Posit Workbench, Posit Connect, and Posit Package Manager.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.120
Starting at the top, we have your data scientists and analysts.

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:37.440
These are the folks writing code and creating insights using Posit Workbench.

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:41.760
And they can use whatever language they want, including R and Python,

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:46.480
and develop in any environment of their choosing, including the RStudio IDE,

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:50.559
JupyterLab, Jupyter Notebooks, as well as Visual Studio Code.

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:55.120
For your R developers, they may be creating insights like Shiny applications,

00:01:55.120 --> 00:02:00.160
pins, R Markdown, or Korto documents, APIs using the Plumber package,

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:03.040
or deploying and monitoring models using Vetiver.

00:02:03.839 --> 00:02:08.320
And for your Python developers, they have a home to create interactive web applications

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:11.440
using Streamlet, Dash, Bokeh, and Shiny.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.759
They can also create documents using Jupyter Notebooks or Korto,

00:02:15.759 --> 00:02:18.320
and APIs using Flask and FastAPI.

00:02:18.479 --> 00:02:21.759
You'll also notice that many of our tools we create here at Posit,

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:24.559
including Korto, Shiny, Pins, and Vetiver,

00:02:24.559 --> 00:02:27.360
are available to both your R and Python developers.

00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:31.759
Now, once the developers create content,

00:02:31.759 --> 00:02:35.039
they need a way to share it with the people that need to see it,

00:02:35.039 --> 00:02:38.720
including decision makers, co-workers, clients,

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:40.639
or maybe even just friends and family.

00:02:41.199 --> 00:02:43.039
That's the role of Posit Connect,

00:02:43.039 --> 00:02:45.199
which is our professional publishing platform.

00:02:45.199 --> 00:02:48.240
Not only does Connect make it easy to share content,

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:50.960
but also control access and performance scaling.

00:02:51.759 --> 00:02:54.399
These settings are usually in the purview of IT,

00:02:54.399 --> 00:02:57.839
but Connect puts these controls in the hands of your data scientists.

00:02:59.119 --> 00:03:01.679
And finally, we have Posit Package Manager,

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:06.800
which helps centralize and organize the great open-source R and Python packages

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:10.399
your team uses for data science, machine learning, and more.

00:03:10.399 --> 00:03:14.000
You can also host internally developed R and Python packages

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.399
and restrict access to specific packages

00:03:16.399 --> 00:03:18.960
based on various user-defined criteria,

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:21.360
including the presence of known vulnerabilities.

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:25.759
In our eyes, an open-source platform without real package management

00:03:25.759 --> 00:03:27.360
is not an open-source platform.

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:31.839
So to start our demo, let's introduce you to Posit Workbench.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:35.919
After logging into Posit Workbench

00:03:35.919 --> 00:03:38.720
using your team's preferred authentication method,

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:40.880
we land on the Posit Workbench homepage.

00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:44.000
On the left-hand side, I'll click the New Session button,

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:45.679
which brings us to a new window

00:03:45.679 --> 00:03:47.759
where I can choose my development environment.

00:03:48.559 --> 00:03:52.720
Currently, Posit Workbench supports JupyterLab and JupyterNotebooks,

00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:55.279
RStudio, and Visual Studio Code.

00:03:56.160 --> 00:03:57.919
Depending on your configuration,

00:03:57.919 --> 00:04:01.759
you can deploy a session on the local Linux machine running Workbench,

00:04:01.759 --> 00:04:04.639
or if you're working in an HPC environment,

00:04:04.639 --> 00:04:08.559
developers have the flexibility to choose the compute workbench

00:04:08.559 --> 00:04:11.600
and the image they would like to deploy their session within.

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:14.639
Let's go ahead and open a new RStudio session.

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:22.720
Once inside the RStudio IDE,

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:24.880
developers can start coding immediately.

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:28.480
Users can easily make connections to external data sources

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:30.000
using a variety of methods,

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.359
including our provided professional ODBC drivers

00:04:33.359 --> 00:04:36.239
to many of the most common databases in the world.

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:39.679
to many of the most common databases available today,

00:04:39.679 --> 00:04:44.239
including Postgres, Snowflake, Redshift, BigQuery, and even Databricks.

00:04:44.959 --> 00:04:47.760
We also added seamless authentication pass-through

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:49.839
from Posit Workbench to Databricks

00:04:49.839 --> 00:04:53.200
so that users can easily start, stop, connect,

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:55.920
and view details of accessible Databricks clusters.

00:04:56.640 --> 00:05:00.480
Users can also easily access their Unity catalog data and models

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:02.480
without ever leaving the RStudio IDE.

00:05:03.119 --> 00:05:04.399
In this workflow video,

00:05:04.399 --> 00:05:07.760
a user is leveraging the R package known as sparklyr

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:10.720
to access some UFO data stored on Databricks

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:11.920
within Posit Workbench.

00:05:12.559 --> 00:05:14.959
Alternatively, the user could access the data

00:05:14.959 --> 00:05:17.040
using the provided ODBC driver.

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:20.959
The quarto document you see in the top left quadrant

00:05:20.959 --> 00:05:22.880
makes use of the Databricks connection

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:26.559
to extract, process, and visualize the UFO data.

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:30.959
Users can also leverage the power of generative AI

00:05:30.959 --> 00:05:32.720
to assist with their development,

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:35.600
including the built-in support for GitHub Copilot

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:38.320
within the RStudio IDE on Posit Workbench.

00:05:39.119 --> 00:05:41.679
In this workflow, a user is creating a model

00:05:41.679 --> 00:05:44.160
using a suite of packages called tidymodels,

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:45.760
which we've developed here at Posit.

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:47.920
As the user writes code,

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:51.359
GitHub Copilot takes in cues from the code and comments

00:05:51.359 --> 00:05:54.880
to provide autocomplete-style suggestions to the developer.

00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:58.160
Additionally, developers can directly access

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:00.320
chat-style large language models,

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:03.839
such as chat-gpt, directly in RStudio

00:06:03.839 --> 00:06:06.559
to create the general structure of a modeling pipeline

00:06:06.559 --> 00:06:07.440
all in one go.

00:06:08.239 --> 00:06:11.200
These generative AI capabilities in Posit Workbench

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:13.839
are also customizable and extensible,

00:06:13.839 --> 00:06:16.239
and users can easily write their own add-ons

00:06:16.239 --> 00:06:17.920
that use self-hosted models.

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:21.040
Once your users have accessed their data,

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:22.959
they can begin creating valuable insights

00:06:22.959 --> 00:06:24.640
to help drive your business forward.

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:27.119
These insights can take many shapes,

00:06:27.119 --> 00:06:30.160
from static reports to interactive web applications.

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:32.640
What you're seeing here in the top-left quadrant

00:06:32.640 --> 00:06:34.959
is something known as a Shiny application.

00:06:34.959 --> 00:06:38.320
Shiny is an open-source package we developed here at Posit

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:41.440
that allows anyone to create interactive web applications

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:43.519
using only R or Python code.

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:46.399
This application was written in R

00:06:46.399 --> 00:06:48.320
and makes use of the tidymodels packages

00:06:48.320 --> 00:06:51.200
we discussed before to create different predictive models.

00:06:51.359 --> 00:06:53.359
We can run this application locally

00:06:53.359 --> 00:06:56.000
within Posit Workbench to see the final product.

00:06:56.799 --> 00:06:59.279
On the left-hand side, we have a drop-down menu

00:06:59.279 --> 00:07:01.279
to select various model types.

00:07:01.279 --> 00:07:02.399
After selecting a model,

00:07:02.399 --> 00:07:04.799
the application executes the modeling process

00:07:04.799 --> 00:07:07.119
in the background and makes predictions

00:07:07.119 --> 00:07:09.839
using a simple dataset containing car data.

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:13.119
Here, we are assessing the accuracy of our models

00:07:13.119 --> 00:07:15.760
by looking at the predicted miles per gallon

00:07:15.760 --> 00:07:17.839
for various cars on the y-axis

00:07:17.839 --> 00:07:20.640
versus actual miles per gallon on the y-axis.

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:24.959
While this example application may seem straightforward,

00:07:24.959 --> 00:07:26.640
it can provide valuable information

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:28.640
about the performance of different models.

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:32.000
These insights can be of immense value to your team,

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:33.279
but only if they are shared

00:07:33.279 --> 00:07:34.880
with the relevant decision-makers.

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:38.160
So how, then, do we share this application with others?

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:40.720
That's where Posit Connect comes into play.

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:42.320
There are a variety of methods

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:44.480
to publish content to Posit Connect,

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:46.799
some of which are as simple as clicking a button.

00:07:47.839 --> 00:07:49.760
At the top of the RStudio IDE

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:53.119
is a button that will kick off the publishing process.

00:07:53.839 --> 00:07:55.519
In the subsequent pop-up menu,

00:07:55.519 --> 00:07:59.119
we first define which files we need to send to Posit Connect.

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:02.959
In this example, it's only our shiny app.r file.

00:08:03.839 --> 00:08:05.440
Next, we define the Connect instance

00:08:05.440 --> 00:08:07.040
we would like to publish to.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:09.760
And finally, we can give our application a name.

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:11.519
I'll leave it as Modeling App,

00:08:11.519 --> 00:08:12.799
and then we click Publish.

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:14.959
Without Posit Team,

00:08:14.959 --> 00:08:18.160
if a user wanted to share this application with others,

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:19.679
the recipients of the app

00:08:19.679 --> 00:08:22.000
would be required to have R installed,

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.480
along with all the necessary R packages

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:26.480
and the correct versions of those packages.

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:28.559
With Posit Connect,

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:31.519
the dependency capturing and environment replication

00:08:31.519 --> 00:08:33.280
is done automatically.

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:34.880
This ensures that the content,

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:36.799
once hosted on Posit Connect,

00:08:36.799 --> 00:08:37.840
runs as intended.

00:08:38.719 --> 00:08:40.799
And here we have the modeling application

00:08:40.799 --> 00:08:42.960
we developed within Posit Workbench,

00:08:42.960 --> 00:08:44.559
now hosted on Posit Connect.

00:08:45.520 --> 00:08:47.840
As the owner of this content on Posit Connect,

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:50.479
I have full control over who has access

00:08:50.479 --> 00:08:52.080
and how the application behaves.

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:53.840
These settings are accessed

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:56.080
by clicking the gear icon in the top right corner.

00:08:56.799 --> 00:08:58.239
In the Access section,

00:08:58.239 --> 00:09:00.479
the first thing you'll notice are the sharing options.

00:09:01.119 --> 00:09:04.000
If you need to ensure that your content remains secure

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:07.520
and is only accessible to specific individuals or groups,

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:09.359
you can choose the bottom option

00:09:09.359 --> 00:09:11.840
and then specify the particular users or groups

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:12.960
in the text box below.

00:09:13.679 --> 00:09:16.000
Similarly, if you want to ensure content

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.080
is only accessible to individuals

00:09:18.080 --> 00:09:20.640
with authenticated access to Posit Connect,

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:22.080
we can select the middle option.

00:09:23.599 --> 00:09:26.239
Finally, to open the content to the public,

00:09:26.239 --> 00:09:28.000
we can select the top option.

00:09:28.799 --> 00:09:30.320
Now, the only thing I need

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:32.239
to share this content with others

00:09:32.239 --> 00:09:34.479
is the content URL at the bottom,

00:09:34.479 --> 00:09:36.559
which can be customized in the text box above.

00:09:37.679 --> 00:09:39.599
Once a viewer clicks the URL,

00:09:39.599 --> 00:09:41.440
they can treat the Shiny application

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:42.880
just like any other website

00:09:42.880 --> 00:09:45.599
and won't need to know anything about R or Shiny.

00:09:46.159 --> 00:09:48.320
Again, the primary goal of Posit Connect

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:49.679
is to make sharing content

00:09:49.679 --> 00:09:51.840
as easy as possible with anyone.

00:09:52.559 --> 00:09:56.000
Now, not all content hosted on Posit Connect is the same,

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:57.119
and in some cases,

00:09:57.119 --> 00:09:59.679
content may only be viewed by a handful of people,

00:09:59.679 --> 00:10:00.640
and in other cases,

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:02.559
it may be viewed by thousands,

00:10:02.559 --> 00:10:03.919
potentially all at once.

00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:08.080
To help tune and scale your applications and APIs,

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:09.440
publishers and administrators

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:11.599
have access to runtime settings.

00:10:12.239 --> 00:10:14.320
These settings can be easily modified

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:16.400
to ensure a good user experience.

00:10:17.359 --> 00:10:20.559
The scheduling option only applies to static content,

00:10:20.559 --> 00:10:21.840
things like R Markdown,

00:10:21.840 --> 00:10:22.799
Jupyter Notebooks,

00:10:22.799 --> 00:10:24.239
and Quarto documents.

00:10:24.239 --> 00:10:26.400
We'll discuss these settings later on in the demo.

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:29.119
Next, we come to the tag setting,

00:10:29.119 --> 00:10:30.960
which allows teams to establish

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:32.880
their own organizational structure

00:10:32.880 --> 00:10:35.119
for content hosted on Posit Connect.

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:38.320
Finally, we have the var setting,

00:10:38.320 --> 00:10:40.799
which provides developers with the capability

00:10:40.799 --> 00:10:42.960
to securely incorporate secrets

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:45.440
such as passwords, keys, and tokens

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:47.200
as environment variables,

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:48.400
thereby avoiding the need

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:50.400
to embed these sensitive details

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:51.599
directly within the code.

00:10:52.479 --> 00:10:55.200
So far, we've used the R programming language

00:10:55.200 --> 00:10:57.359
and various open source tools and packages

00:10:57.359 --> 00:11:00.080
to create and interact with machine learning models.

00:11:00.719 --> 00:11:02.239
We are going to switch gears

00:11:02.239 --> 00:11:04.559
and now use Python within Posit Team

00:11:04.559 --> 00:11:07.039
to monitor the performance of a model.

00:11:07.039 --> 00:11:09.840
At Posit, we've developed an open source package

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:10.799
named Vetiver,

00:11:10.799 --> 00:11:12.559
available in both R and Python.

00:11:13.200 --> 00:11:15.440
This package aids in the deployment,

00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:17.039
versioning, and monitoring

00:11:17.039 --> 00:11:18.719
of machine learning models,

00:11:18.719 --> 00:11:19.840
a field commonly known

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:21.599
as machine learning operations,

00:11:21.599 --> 00:11:22.719
or MLOps.

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:24.960
Let's use Vetiver to monitor

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:26.239
the performance of a model

00:11:26.239 --> 00:11:28.719
using Python within VS Code

00:11:28.719 --> 00:11:30.080
running on Posit Workbench.

00:11:30.799 --> 00:11:31.840
To get started,

00:11:31.840 --> 00:11:34.559
let's open a new session of VS Code.

00:11:34.559 --> 00:11:36.479
A major benefit of Posit Workbench

00:11:36.479 --> 00:11:38.080
is you can have multiple sessions

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:40.400
of various IDEs running at the same time.

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:42.880
Within this session of VS Code,

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:44.960
I'll first open a Quarto document

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:46.719
which contains our Vetiver workflow.

00:11:47.359 --> 00:11:50.239
Quarto is a Posit-created open source tool

00:11:50.239 --> 00:11:52.159
for scientific and technical publishing.

00:11:52.719 --> 00:11:55.679
This Quarto document was written using Python,

00:11:55.679 --> 00:11:57.119
but Quarto also supports

00:11:57.119 --> 00:11:58.960
other popular data science languages,

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:01.200
including R, Julia, and Observable.

00:12:01.919 --> 00:12:03.039
In the Python code,

00:12:03.039 --> 00:12:04.400
we are creating a model

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:06.559
and then measuring the performance of the model

00:12:06.559 --> 00:12:07.919
as new data is captured.

00:12:08.479 --> 00:12:10.239
Let's preview the Quarto document

00:12:10.239 --> 00:12:11.840
and view the performance metrics.

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:14.080
We'll get a live preview window

00:12:14.080 --> 00:12:15.919
that shows the rendered Quarto document

00:12:15.919 --> 00:12:17.679
in HTML format,

00:12:17.679 --> 00:12:19.919
thanks to the Quarto VS Code extension.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:22.080
It's also worth noting

00:12:22.080 --> 00:12:24.239
that we could view this live preview

00:12:24.239 --> 00:12:26.799
using the Posit Workbench VS Code extension

00:12:26.799 --> 00:12:28.559
that provides secure proxying

00:12:28.559 --> 00:12:30.559
to the local development environment.

00:12:30.559 --> 00:12:32.320
This is great for viewing documents

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:34.479
or testing interactive applications.

00:12:35.119 --> 00:12:36.640
Here we have three plots

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:39.200
that show three commonly collected metrics

00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:40.640
for model performance,

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:42.159
mean absolute error,

00:12:42.159 --> 00:12:43.359
mean squared error,

00:12:43.359 --> 00:12:44.479
and the r-squared value.

00:12:45.039 --> 00:12:46.479
These valuable metrics,

00:12:46.479 --> 00:12:48.159
just like our Shiny application,

00:12:48.159 --> 00:12:50.320
will likely need to be shared with others.

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:52.320
So let's publish the Quarto document

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:53.280
to Posit Connect.

00:12:53.919 --> 00:12:54.880
In this example,

00:12:54.880 --> 00:12:55.760
we are going to use

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:59.039
the rsconnect command line interface tool

00:12:59.039 --> 00:13:01.280
to assist with the dependency capturing

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:02.799
and publishing to Posit Connect.

00:13:03.599 --> 00:13:04.320
In the terminal,

00:13:04.320 --> 00:13:05.520
at the bottom of the screen,

00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:07.520
I'll type out the following command,

00:13:07.520 --> 00:13:09.919
rsconnect deploy Quarto.

00:13:10.559 --> 00:13:11.599
And then provide the name

00:13:11.599 --> 00:13:12.960
of our Quarto document,

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:15.200
which is mlops.qmd.

00:13:15.919 --> 00:13:16.960
I'll hit enter,

00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:19.280
and then rsconnect will take care of the rest.

00:13:19.840 --> 00:13:21.599
Just like our Shiny application,

00:13:21.599 --> 00:13:23.039
my development environment,

00:13:23.039 --> 00:13:24.799
including my Python version,

00:13:24.799 --> 00:13:26.799
packages, and package versions,

00:13:26.799 --> 00:13:28.559
is captured and sent to Connect.

00:13:29.200 --> 00:13:31.119
Once Connect replicates my environment,

00:13:31.119 --> 00:13:33.440
it will then deploy the Quarto document.

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:34.239
And here it is,

00:13:34.239 --> 00:13:35.760
now hosted on Posit Connect.

00:13:36.880 --> 00:13:38.640
Just like our Shiny application,

00:13:38.640 --> 00:13:41.280
I have access to the same content settings

00:13:41.280 --> 00:13:42.799
for our Quarto document,

00:13:42.799 --> 00:13:44.159
including the sharing settings

00:13:44.159 --> 00:13:45.280
that we discussed earlier

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:47.039
for managing access to content.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.400
However, for reports like Quarto,

00:13:50.400 --> 00:13:52.799
R Markdown, and Jupyter Notebooks,

00:13:52.799 --> 00:13:54.880
the source code can be re-executed

00:13:54.880 --> 00:13:56.479
on a schedule of your choosing.

00:13:57.119 --> 00:13:59.359
This is great for automating repetitive tasks

00:13:59.359 --> 00:14:01.359
or streamlining data science workflows.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:03.440
Since our machine learning model

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:06.239
performance metrics are calculated weekly,

00:14:06.239 --> 00:14:07.760
let's have this Quarto document

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:09.520
automatically run every Monday.

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:12.239
I'll first select the schedule tab,

00:14:12.239 --> 00:14:13.280
and then I have the option

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:14.400
to choose my time zone.

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:17.359
Next, I'll select the frequency,

00:14:17.359 --> 00:14:18.880
which I'll change to weekly,

00:14:18.880 --> 00:14:20.479
and have it run every Monday.

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:24.400
Finally, I have two options at the bottom.

00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:27.039
The first option asks to publish the output

00:14:27.039 --> 00:14:28.000
after it's generated.

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:30.000
Since the plots will change

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:31.679
every time you run this document,

00:14:31.679 --> 00:14:33.200
I'll make sure to keep this selected

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:35.280
so that Quarto content on Connect

00:14:35.280 --> 00:14:36.320
is always up to date

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:37.440
with the latest metrics.

00:14:38.159 --> 00:14:39.440
For the second option,

00:14:39.440 --> 00:14:40.799
Posit Connect can be set up

00:14:40.799 --> 00:14:42.080
with an email client

00:14:42.080 --> 00:14:43.760
that enables you to send emails

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:45.840
to users containing a direct link

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:47.599
to this content whenever it runs.

00:14:48.320 --> 00:14:50.640
In the case of Quarto and R Markdown,

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:51.919
you also have the option

00:14:51.919 --> 00:14:53.840
to include plots and tables

00:14:53.840 --> 00:14:55.599
directly within the email,

00:14:55.599 --> 00:14:57.760
offering an additional valuable way

00:14:57.760 --> 00:14:59.119
to share data insights.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:01.359
Open source data science

00:15:01.359 --> 00:15:03.200
without proper package management

00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:05.679
can result in a painful coding experience

00:15:05.679 --> 00:15:07.359
and non-reproducible workflows.

00:15:08.080 --> 00:15:09.919
That's precisely why we created

00:15:09.919 --> 00:15:11.200
Posit Package Manager,

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:12.559
which is designed to ensure

00:15:12.559 --> 00:15:13.520
that your open source

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:15.039
data science workflows

00:15:15.039 --> 00:15:16.960
function seamlessly and reliably.

00:15:17.679 --> 00:15:19.919
In fact, all the machine learning analyses

00:15:19.919 --> 00:15:21.840
we've done so far in this demo

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:23.679
were using open source packages

00:15:23.679 --> 00:15:25.520
installed from Posit Package Manager.

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:27.919
Let's start with a quick overview

00:15:27.919 --> 00:15:29.359
of Posit Package Manager,

00:15:29.359 --> 00:15:31.520
and we'll discuss many of its amazing features

00:15:31.520 --> 00:15:32.239
along the way.

00:15:32.960 --> 00:15:34.080
Once your administrator

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:35.679
installs Package Manager,

00:15:35.679 --> 00:15:37.520
users can access the homepage,

00:15:37.520 --> 00:15:38.880
where they are immediately greeted

00:15:38.880 --> 00:15:41.280
with options to select various packages

00:15:41.280 --> 00:15:42.479
from repositories

00:15:42.479 --> 00:15:44.000
that your team can customize.

00:15:44.880 --> 00:15:46.479
This instance of Package Manager

00:15:46.479 --> 00:15:47.919
has 11 repositories

00:15:48.479 --> 00:15:51.280
and is serving over 26,000 packages

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:52.239
from CRAN,

00:15:52.239 --> 00:15:53.919
which is the primary repository

00:15:53.919 --> 00:15:54.960
for our developers,

00:15:55.679 --> 00:15:57.760
as well as over half a million

00:15:57.760 --> 00:15:59.200
PyPI packages,

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:00.799
which is the primary repository

00:16:00.799 --> 00:16:01.919
for Python developers.

00:16:02.719 --> 00:16:03.440
Let's take a look

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:04.960
at the various repositories

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:07.039
in this instance of Package Manager.

00:16:07.119 --> 00:16:09.200
Here I have five R repositories,

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:11.280
including a mirror of CRAN,

00:16:11.280 --> 00:16:13.119
and five Python repositories,

00:16:13.119 --> 00:16:14.719
including a mirror of PyPI.

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:16.880
I can also serve packages

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:18.080
from Bioconductor,

00:16:18.080 --> 00:16:19.840
which is a popular repository

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:21.520
for bioinformatic analyses.

00:16:22.159 --> 00:16:23.200
And you'll also notice

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:24.799
an internal repository

00:16:24.799 --> 00:16:26.159
for both R and Python.

00:16:26.799 --> 00:16:28.640
These are repositories that serve

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:29.919
internally developed R

00:16:29.919 --> 00:16:31.280
and Python packages,

00:16:31.280 --> 00:16:33.039
making it easier to collaborate

00:16:33.039 --> 00:16:34.400
and share code with colleagues.

00:16:35.280 --> 00:16:36.880
Some of the other repositories

00:16:36.880 --> 00:16:38.320
configured in this environment

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:40.719
include subsets of both CRAN and PyPI,

00:16:41.359 --> 00:16:42.640
blended repositories,

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:43.919
which allow you to combine

00:16:43.919 --> 00:16:45.919
both internally developed packages

00:16:45.919 --> 00:16:47.919
with subsets of either CRAN or PyPI.

00:16:48.640 --> 00:16:49.840
And finally, you'll notice

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:51.200
a block repository

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:52.559
for both R and Python.

00:16:53.359 --> 00:16:55.039
This is an added security feature

00:16:55.039 --> 00:16:56.320
of Posit Package Manager,

00:16:56.320 --> 00:16:57.679
which allows you to block

00:16:57.679 --> 00:16:59.679
high-risk and unwanted packages

00:16:59.679 --> 00:17:01.280
based on various criteria,

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:02.960
including specific licenses

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:04.239
or known vulnerabilities.

00:17:05.040 --> 00:17:06.319
Let's select CRAN

00:17:06.319 --> 00:17:07.439
and discuss how users

00:17:07.439 --> 00:17:09.119
would go about installing packages

00:17:09.119 --> 00:17:10.160
from this repository.

00:17:10.719 --> 00:17:11.839
Clicking the Setup button

00:17:11.839 --> 00:17:13.439
will take me to a new page

00:17:13.439 --> 00:17:14.479
where Package Manager

00:17:14.479 --> 00:17:15.920
will prompt me with questions

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:17.040
regarding my environment.

00:17:17.839 --> 00:17:19.439
The first question has me select

00:17:19.439 --> 00:17:20.400
my operating system.

00:17:21.280 --> 00:17:22.959
If you're using Posit Workbench,

00:17:22.959 --> 00:17:24.479
then you would select Linux

00:17:24.479 --> 00:17:25.439
and then choose the Linux

00:17:25.439 --> 00:17:26.400
distribution below.

00:17:27.199 --> 00:17:29.520
Another feature of Posit Package Manager

00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:30.400
is that it can serve

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:31.760
R and Python packages

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:34.160
as pre-compiled Linux binaries,

00:17:34.160 --> 00:17:35.520
which can dramatically increase

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:37.119
the package installation speed

00:17:37.119 --> 00:17:37.920
for your users.

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:39.839
The next question asks

00:17:39.839 --> 00:17:42.000
if I want to freeze package versions

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.680
to enhance reproducibility.

00:17:44.319 --> 00:17:45.439
Open-source packages

00:17:45.439 --> 00:17:46.640
tend to evolve quickly,

00:17:46.640 --> 00:17:47.359
which is great

00:17:47.359 --> 00:17:49.280
for cutting-edge data science.

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:51.040
However, there may be instances

00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:52.640
where new package versions

00:17:52.640 --> 00:17:53.599
are not compatible

00:17:53.599 --> 00:17:54.959
with other packages

00:17:54.959 --> 00:17:55.920
or code your team

00:17:55.920 --> 00:17:56.959
has previously developed.

00:17:57.760 --> 00:17:59.199
To prevent these conflicts,

00:17:59.199 --> 00:18:00.319
Posit Package Manager

00:18:00.319 --> 00:18:02.160
allows you to freeze a repository

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:03.680
to a specific date

00:18:03.680 --> 00:18:05.040
using the calendar below.

00:18:05.599 --> 00:18:07.359
Which helps lock package versions

00:18:07.359 --> 00:18:08.640
in place and prevent

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:09.920
any potential conflicts.

00:18:10.800 --> 00:18:12.160
Finally, after choosing

00:18:12.160 --> 00:18:13.599
my development environment,

00:18:13.599 --> 00:18:14.560
I'm presented with

00:18:14.560 --> 00:18:16.640
a customized repository URL.

00:18:17.439 --> 00:18:18.800
Reading through the URL,

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:19.760
you can see I'm using

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:20.959
the eval instance of

00:18:20.959 --> 00:18:22.560
Posit Package Manager,

00:18:22.560 --> 00:18:24.400
the CRAN repository,

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:26.479
and I will install Linux binaries

00:18:26.479 --> 00:18:28.719
that are frozen to a specific date.

00:18:28.719 --> 00:18:29.680
In this example,

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:32.400
that date is January 26, 2024.

00:18:32.959 --> 00:18:34.800
Below the repository URL

00:18:34.800 --> 00:18:36.160
are the setup instructions

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:38.079
to help users and administrators

00:18:38.079 --> 00:18:39.760
configure this repository

00:18:39.760 --> 00:18:40.959
in the development environment

00:18:40.959 --> 00:18:41.839
I selected above.

00:18:42.959 --> 00:18:44.079
For our previous

00:18:44.079 --> 00:18:46.560
machine learning operations analysis,

00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:47.760
we used vetiver,

00:18:47.760 --> 00:18:49.359
which is an open-source package

00:18:49.359 --> 00:18:50.959
in both Python and R.

00:18:50.959 --> 00:18:51.760
Let's take a look

00:18:51.760 --> 00:18:53.199
at the vetiver R package

00:18:53.199 --> 00:18:54.560
within this repository.

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:56.959
Once the repository URL

00:18:56.959 --> 00:18:57.920
has been configured

00:18:57.920 --> 00:18:59.520
in the developer's environment,

00:18:59.520 --> 00:19:00.479
all they need to do

00:19:00.479 --> 00:19:02.880
is run the install.packages function

00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:03.839
to install vetiver.

00:19:04.479 --> 00:19:05.520
Below, you can get

00:19:05.520 --> 00:19:07.599
some more information about vetiver,

00:19:07.599 --> 00:19:09.520
including the most recent version

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:11.599
and any known security vulnerabilities.

00:19:12.239 --> 00:19:14.160
The vulnerabilities are reported

00:19:14.160 --> 00:19:15.439
based on a database

00:19:15.439 --> 00:19:17.839
of known open-source vulnerabilities

00:19:17.839 --> 00:19:19.359
called the OSV project.

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:21.680
vetiver does not have

00:19:21.680 --> 00:19:23.199
any known vulnerabilities,

00:19:23.199 --> 00:19:24.160
but if I navigate

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:25.359
to another R package

00:19:25.359 --> 00:19:26.560
called commonmark,

00:19:26.560 --> 00:19:27.520
you can see what

00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:28.880
known vulnerabilities exist.

00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:32.079
Administrators can also block packages

00:19:32.079 --> 00:19:33.520
with known vulnerabilities,

00:19:33.599 --> 00:19:34.479
which prevents users

00:19:34.479 --> 00:19:35.439
from installing them

00:19:35.439 --> 00:19:36.239
into their local

00:19:36.239 --> 00:19:37.280
development environment.

00:19:38.479 --> 00:19:40.959
In summary, Posit's tools excel

00:19:40.959 --> 00:19:42.079
in leveraging code

00:19:42.079 --> 00:19:43.119
to produce highly

00:19:43.119 --> 00:19:44.560
customized analyses

00:19:44.560 --> 00:19:46.640
and visually engaging data insights

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:47.920
like interactive reports

00:19:47.920 --> 00:19:48.800
and applications.

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:51.199
This customization is what

00:19:51.199 --> 00:19:52.719
truly sets Posit apart

00:19:52.719 --> 00:19:53.920
from other analytic

00:19:53.920 --> 00:19:55.040
and BI platforms.

00:19:55.599 --> 00:19:57.359
Moreover, Posit Teams

00:19:57.359 --> 00:19:58.800
significantly contributes

00:19:58.800 --> 00:19:59.920
to enhanced data

00:19:59.920 --> 00:20:01.439
and software governance,

00:20:01.439 --> 00:20:02.959
making it a valuable asset

00:20:02.959 --> 00:20:05.359
for your team's data-driven endeavors.

